LVM — flexible volume management.

LVM, the logical volume manager, is a layer that sits between your partitions and your filesystems, and it solves a real, painful problem: with plain partitions, resizing is a nightmare. LVM lets you treat multiple physical disks or partitions as one big pool of storage, and then carve logical volumes out of that pool, and, crucially, resize them on the fly, while they're in use, without losing data.

There's a three-layer model, and it's worth memorizing the vocabulary. At the bottom are physical volumes, PVs: your real partitions or disks, like slash-dev-sdb-one, that you've marked for LVM's use. You aggregate those PVs into a volume group, a VG: one big pool of storage with a name, like datavg. And then you carve that volume group into logical volumes, LVs, which behave just like partitions, one might be appdata, another logs. Finally, you put an ordinary filesystem, ext4 or xfs, on top of each logical volume.

Creating LVM follows that same bottom-up order. Step one, sudo pvcreate on your partitions, to mark them as physical volumes. Step two, sudo vgcreate to pool them into a named volume group. Step three, sudo lvcreate dash-capital-L for a size and dash-n for a name, to carve out a logical volume. And step four, mkfs to put a filesystem on it, then mount it. To inspect each layer, there's a matching trio of commands: pvs, vgs, and lvs for quick summaries, or the longer pvdisplay, vgdisplay, lvdisplay for detail.

But here's the superpower, the whole reason LVM exists: growing a logical volume live. You run sudo lvextend dash-capital-L plus-five-G dash-r on the volume, and it grows the volume by five gigabytes and, because of that dash-r flag, resizes the filesystem on top of it in the very same command. No unmounting, no downtime. And if the pool itself runs out of space, you just add another disk: pvcreate it, then vgextend to fold it into the volume group, and now you have more room to grow. Shrinking, by contrast, is only supported on ext4, not XFS, and it requires unmounting first, so the rule of thumb is: growing is the LVM win, do that whenever you can. LVM also does instant, space-efficient snapshots with lvcreate dash-s, which are perfect for taking a consistent backup while the original stays in use.
